Note:
==============================================================================
Instant - Monotonic Timestamp Primitive
==============================================================================

An Instant represents a point on the monotonic clock, expressed as a single
Integer holding nanoseconds since an arbitrary, OS-defined epoch (typically
the boot moment). Instants are immune to wall-clock skew (NTP adjustments,
manual clock changes, leap-second smearing) and are the ONLY time source
suitable for measuring elapsed durations, scheduling timeouts, profiling,
and any cause-effect ordering that must hold across daylight-saving
transitions and admin clock corrections.

A 64-bit signed nanosecond counter covers approximately 292 years from its
reference point, which is sufficient for any process lifetime, any container
restart cycle, and any conceivable monotonic measurement need. Cross-machine
correlation MUST use a wall-clock source (DateTime/UTC), never an Instant.

Backing syscall:
  - POSIX clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, &ts) - Linux, Darwin, *BSD, illumos
  - Windows: QueryPerformanceCounter through the windows_*_syscall_2 router
  - The platform syscall router resolves the correct ABI per target.

References:
  - POSIX.1-2017 clock_gettime, clockid_t (IEEE Std 1003.1-2017)
  - Linux man-pages: clock_gettime(2), clockid_t(7)
  - Apple Open Source: xnu/bsd/kern/kern_time.c
  - RFC 5905 §6 (NTP terminology: "ideal clock", "wall clock" distinction)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: POSIX clockid_t constants (stable across all POSIX-conformant systems)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CLOCK_REALTIME as Integer is 0
Constant CLOCK_MONOTONIC as Integer is 1
Constant CLOCK_PROCESS_CPUTIME_ID as Integer is 2
Constant CLOCK_THREAD_CPUTIME_ID as Integer is 3
Constant CLOCK_MONOTONIC_RAW as Integer is 4
Constant CLOCK_REALTIME_COARSE as Integer is 5
Constant CLOCK_MONOTONIC_COARSE as Integer is 6
Constant CLOCK_BOOTTIME as Integer is 7
Constant CLOCK_TAI as Integer is 11

Note: timespec layout: { tv_sec: int64 (offset 0), tv_nsec: int64 (offset 8) }
Constant TIMESPEC_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant TIMESPEC_SEC_OFFSET as Integer is 0
Constant TIMESPEC_NSEC_OFFSET as Integer is 8

Constant NANOS_PER_SECOND as Integer is 1000000000

Note: Error sentinels for instant_now failure paths (rare: clock unavailable).
Constant INSTANT_ERR_CLOCK_UNAVAILABLE as Integer is -1
Constant INSTANT_ERR_NULL_BUFFER as Integer is -2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public API
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "instant_now" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the current monotonic clock reading as nanoseconds since the
    OS-defined monotonic epoch. Used by every elapsed-time measurement,
    timeout deadline, profiler probe, and ordering check in the system.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a 16-byte timespec on the owned heap, issues a
    clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, &ts) via the platform syscall router
    (syscall_2 with SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME), then computes
    tv_sec * 1_000_000_000 + tv_nsec. On clock_gettime failure (negative
    return), surfaces INSTANT_ERR_CLOCK_UNAVAILABLE so the caller can
    distinguish a genuine zero reading from a syscall error.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One small heap allocation plus one syscall. Linux fast-paths
    CLOCK_MONOTONIC through the vDSO (no kernel transition), bringing
    total cost to ~20-50 ns on contemporary x86-64. Allocation cost
    dominates; callers in hot loops should pass a pre-allocated buffer
    to instant_now_into.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read-only syscall, no privilege required, no information leak.
    Monotonic clock value carries no PII and is not stable across reboots.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let timespec_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIMESPEC_SIZE
    If timespec_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return INSTANT_ERR_NULL_BUFFER
    End If
    Let syscall_num be proc SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME from Syscall
    Let rc be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with syscall_num, CLOCK_MONOTONIC, timespec_ptr
    If rc is less than 0:
        Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with timespec_ptr
        Return INSTANT_ERR_CLOCK_UNAVAILABLE
    End If
    Let tv_sec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_SEC_OFFSET
    Let tv_nsec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_NSEC_OFFSET
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from Layout with timespec_ptr
    Let total_ns be tv_sec multiplied by NANOS_PER_SECOND
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus tv_nsec
    Return total_ns
End Process

Process called "instant_now_into" takes timespec_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Zero-allocation variant of instant_now for hot loops and profilers.
    Caller provides a 16-byte buffer (TIMESPEC_SIZE) and receives the
    nanosecond reading as the return value, with the raw timespec written
    into the buffer for callers who need separate seconds / nanoseconds.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same syscall sequence as instant_now but skips the alloc/free pair.
    Validates the input pointer; a null pointer returns
    INSTANT_ERR_NULL_BUFFER. After the syscall, reads tv_sec / tv_nsec
    out of the supplied buffer and folds them into a single nanosecond
    counter.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Removes the heap allocation hot-path from instant_now. Suitable for
    inner-loop deadline checks. Combined with the Linux vDSO fast path
    this stays in the 20-40 ns regime on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned buffer. The function performs no bounds inference on
    the buffer beyond requiring a non-null pointer; supplying a buffer
    smaller than TIMESPEC_SIZE is a programmer error and would corrupt
    adjacent memory the same way as any direct syscall_2 misuse.
    @End Security_Scope
    If timespec_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return INSTANT_ERR_NULL_BUFFER
    End If
    Let syscall_num be proc SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME from Syscall
    Let rc be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with syscall_num, CLOCK_MONOTONIC, timespec_ptr
    If rc is less than 0:
        Return INSTANT_ERR_CLOCK_UNAVAILABLE
    End If
    Let tv_sec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_SEC_OFFSET
    Let tv_nsec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_NSEC_OFFSET
    Let total_ns be tv_sec multiplied by NANOS_PER_SECOND
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus tv_nsec
    Return total_ns
End Process

Process called "instant_now_raw_clock" takes clock_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    General-purpose reader for any POSIX clockid_t. CLOCK_MONOTONIC is
    the default exposed by instant_now; this entry point lets advanced
    callers reach CLOCK_REALTIME (wall clock), CLOCK_TAI (atomic time
    with leap-second jumps removed - see time_reference.runa), or the
    process / thread CPU-time counters used by profilers.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same syscall path as instant_now but with the caller-chosen clock_id.
    Returns the nanosecond reading combined from tv_sec and tv_nsec, or
    a negative error sentinel on syscall failure.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Identical cost profile to instant_now. CLOCK_MONOTONIC_COARSE and
    CLOCK_REALTIME_COARSE are cheaper (~1-2 ns via vDSO with reduced
    precision) when sub-millisecond resolution is unnecessary.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    All POSIX clocks are readable without privilege. CLOCK_REALTIME is
    affected by admin clock adjustments and MUST NOT be used for
    elapsed-time measurement.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let timespec_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIMESPEC_SIZE
    If timespec_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return INSTANT_ERR_NULL_BUFFER
    End If
    Let syscall_num be proc SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME from Syscall
    Let rc be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with syscall_num, clock_id, timespec_ptr
    If rc is less than 0:
        Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with timespec_ptr
        Return INSTANT_ERR_CLOCK_UNAVAILABLE
    End If
    Let tv_sec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_SEC_OFFSET
    Let tv_nsec be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, TIMESPEC_NSEC_OFFSET
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from Layout with timespec_ptr
    Let total_ns be tv_sec multiplied by NANOS_PER_SECOND
    Set total_ns to total_ns plus tv_nsec
    Return total_ns
End Process

Process called "instant_elapsed" takes start as Integer, end_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the nanosecond delta between two Instants. By contract
    end_value is the later reading and start is the earlier reading,
    so the result is non-negative for any well-formed pair. Returns a
    Duration-compatible signed nanosecond count; if the caller has
    reversed the arguments the result will be negative, which is the
    same convention as POSIX timersub.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single integer subtraction. No overflow check is required: both
    operands originate from clock_gettime on the same machine within
    the 292-year monotonic window, so their difference fits trivially
    inside a signed 64-bit Integer.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One arithmetic instruction. Inline-friendly.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function. No side effects, no syscalls.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return end_value minus start
End Process

Process called "instant_add_duration" takes i as Integer, d_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Advances or rewinds an Instant by the supplied Duration (expressed
    in signed nanoseconds via duration_to_nanoseconds). Used by deadline
    arithmetic - "fire this timer 50 ms from now" - throughout schedulers,
    timeouts, and rate limiters.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Integer addition with no overflow check, for the same reason as
    instant_elapsed: any plausible deadline horizon stays well inside
    the monotonic 64-bit range. Pass a negative d_ns to subtract.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single instruction; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function. No side effects.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return i plus d_ns
End Process

Process called "instant_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Three-way comparison primitive returning -1 if a precedes b, 0 if
    they are simultaneous, +1 if a follows b. The strict ordering rule
    follows the C++ <=> and Rust Ordering conventions so callers can
    chain compares without ambiguity.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two integer compares with early return. Branchless variants exist
    (e.g. (a > b) - (a < b)) but the compiler already collapses the
    pair of branches to a flags+set sequence on x86-64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares + two branches; ~1 cycle on modern out-of-order cores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is less than b:
        Return -1
    End If
    If a is greater than b:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "instant_is_before" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Predicate form of instant_compare for callers that want a binary
    result. Returns 1 if a strictly precedes b, 0 otherwise.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single signed compare.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One compare, one set; inlined to a flag check.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is less than b:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "instant_is_after" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Predicate form returning 1 if a strictly follows b, 0 otherwise.
    Mirrors instant_is_before. Equality returns 0 in both directions,
    matching strict ordering semantics.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single signed compare.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same as instant_is_before.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is greater than b:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "instant_min" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the earlier of two Instants. Useful for deadline composition:
    "wait until the soonest of these expirations".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Branch on signed compare; returns the smaller operand.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Compiles to cmp + cmov on x86-64. Single cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    End If
    Return b
End Process

Process called "instant_max" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the later of two Instants. Useful for "latest start" /
    "no-earlier-than" deadline computations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Branch on signed compare; returns the larger operand.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    cmp + cmov on x86-64. Single cycle.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is greater than b:
        Return a
    End If
    Return b
End Process

Process called "instant_to_nanoseconds" takes i as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Identity accessor. Provided so callers can move between the Instant
    abstraction and raw nanoseconds without reaching into the
    implementation. If the storage representation ever changes (e.g. to
    a 128-bit limb pair) this becomes the single migration point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the input unchanged.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Free; compiler folds away.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return i
End Process

Process called "instant_from_nanoseconds" takes ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of instant_to_nanoseconds. Constructs an Instant from a raw
    nanosecond counter. Used by deserialisers and test fixtures.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the input unchanged.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Free; compiler folds away.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function. The caller is responsible for sourcing ns from a
    monotonic clock; passing a wall-clock value defeats the type's
    skew-immunity contract.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return ns
End Process
